<Layout
    title="Hey, I'm Ethan"
    description="Why I started Eco Living Journey (and why preparedness doesn't require a massive budget)."
    pubDate={new Date('February 26 2026')}
>
    
    <img src="/ethan.jpg" alt="Ethan from Eco Living Journey" style="width: 100%; max-width: 600px; border-radius: 12px; margin-bottom: 20px;" />

    <h2>Hi, I'm Ethan. I believe true independence starts with your power supply.</h2>
    
    <p>
        If you look around today, the power grid is getting less reliable, and "preparedness" is often marketed as something only rich people can afford. 
    </p>

    <p>
        I started <strong>Eco Living Journey</strong> because I realized the industry was overcomplicating things. True sustainability isn't about buying expensive eco-products or living in a bunker. It is about <strong>energy independence, practical off-grid solutions, and knowing exactly what to do when the grid goes down.</strong>
    </p>

    <p>
        I'm not a doomsday guru. I'm just a normal guy figuring out how to build a resilient, self-reliant home on a strict budget. I do the math, I test the gear, and I share exactly what works.
    </p>

    <h3>What you will actually find here:</h3>
    <ul>
        <li style="margin-bottom: 10px;"><strong>The Blackout Math:</strong> No guesswork. I break down exactly what size batteries and solar generators you need to run your essential appliances.</li>
        <li style="margin-bottom: 10px;"><strong>Honest Gear Reviews:</strong> If a $2,000 power station is overpriced garbage, I'll tell you.</li>
        <li style="margin-bottom: 10px;"><strong>Practical Self-Reliance:</strong> Simple, actionable steps to protect your food supply, your family, and your peace of mind.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
        You don't need a massive budget to secure your home. Stick around, and let's build your backup plan together.
    </p>
</Layout>